Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.479
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:05.479 --> 00:00:07.020
NATE STANIFORTH:
Thank you very much.

00:00:07.020 --> 00:00:07.520
Thank you.

00:00:07.520 --> 00:00:09.930
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:09.930 --> 00:00:12.840
Thanks very much for having
me to Google headquarters.

00:00:12.840 --> 00:00:13.950
I'm very glad to be here.

00:00:13.950 --> 00:00:18.780
Here's my plan for the
next 45 minutes or so.

00:00:18.780 --> 00:00:20.610
I'd like to talk to
you about the book.

00:00:20.610 --> 00:00:22.200
And I'm happy to
answer any questions

00:00:22.200 --> 00:00:24.300
you have at the end of this.

00:00:24.300 --> 00:00:30.480
But it occurs to me that if
I'm talking about magic as I

00:00:30.480 --> 00:00:33.840
see it, and you're sitting
there thinking of laser beams,

00:00:33.840 --> 00:00:35.880
and smoke machines, and
tight leather pants,

00:00:35.880 --> 00:00:37.560
and top hats, and
rabbits, and Job

00:00:37.560 --> 00:00:39.780
from "Arrested
Development," we're

00:00:39.780 --> 00:00:41.460
never going to
understand each other.

00:00:41.460 --> 00:00:43.830
So I'd like to start
by just telling you

00:00:43.830 --> 00:00:46.440
a little bit of my story.

00:00:46.440 --> 00:00:51.270
And at some point in the
middle of that, it will pivot,

00:00:51.270 --> 00:00:53.280
and we'll go from there.

00:00:53.280 --> 00:00:56.430
So I became a
magician by accident

00:00:56.430 --> 00:00:58.140
when I was a nine year old.

00:00:58.140 --> 00:01:00.532
I read the "Lord of
the Rings" books.

00:01:00.532 --> 00:01:02.240
You've seen the movies
or read the books?

00:01:02.240 --> 00:01:02.820
Yeah.

00:01:02.820 --> 00:01:04.739
So there's this scene
at the beginning

00:01:04.739 --> 00:01:06.330
of the first "Lord
of the Rings" book

00:01:06.330 --> 00:01:10.230
where the wizard Gandalf
is at a birthday party,

00:01:10.230 --> 00:01:14.310
and he uses magic to shoot these
magical fireworks into the sky.

00:01:14.310 --> 00:01:16.530
And it turns into this
dragon, and swoops down,

00:01:16.530 --> 00:01:18.840
and terrifies everybody.

00:01:18.840 --> 00:01:20.970
And I wanted to be
able to do that.

00:01:20.970 --> 00:01:22.530
Because I thought
that if I could

00:01:22.530 --> 00:01:25.420
do that on the playground,
I would be unstoppable.

00:01:25.420 --> 00:01:28.210
And I very much wanted
to be unstoppable.

00:01:28.210 --> 00:01:32.730
So I went-- nine is an unusual
age, because you're old enough

00:01:32.730 --> 00:01:36.000
to get through 1,300 pages
of pretty obscure fantasy

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:38.910
literature, and young enough,
at the end of that time,

00:01:38.910 --> 00:01:42.300
to still hold out hope
that maybe there's

00:01:42.300 --> 00:01:44.610
such a thing as real
magic in the world.

00:01:44.610 --> 00:01:46.770
So I finished the "Lord
of the Rings" books,

00:01:46.770 --> 00:01:49.770
and I went to the adult
section of the library looking

00:01:49.770 --> 00:01:53.100
for a book of spells that I
could do on the playground.

00:01:53.100 --> 00:01:56.140
This was my moment.

00:01:56.140 --> 00:01:59.520
I was going to
crush it like that.

00:01:59.520 --> 00:02:03.720
What I learned instead was that
that's not how magic works.

00:02:03.720 --> 00:02:05.580
But I found a book
of sleight of hand,

00:02:05.580 --> 00:02:09.289
and I learned my first
really great piece of magic.

00:02:09.289 --> 00:02:10.539
And it's very simple.

00:02:10.539 --> 00:02:12.240
You put a coin your hand.

00:02:12.240 --> 00:02:17.220
When you close your hand and
open it, the coin disappears.

00:02:17.220 --> 00:02:21.130
The thing about magic tricks
is that when they are bad,

00:02:21.130 --> 00:02:24.150
they are worse than
just about anything,

00:02:24.150 --> 00:02:26.460
because it just
looks like a trick.

00:02:26.460 --> 00:02:29.970
But when you take a magic
trick and push it far enough

00:02:29.970 --> 00:02:32.580
towards excellence, there
is this tipping point

00:02:32.580 --> 00:02:34.560
where it no longer looks
like a trick, where

00:02:34.560 --> 00:02:39.180
it looks like an actual
supernatural event.

00:02:39.180 --> 00:02:43.020
And I became obsessed
with this coin trick.

00:02:43.020 --> 00:02:44.880
I bet I put in--

00:02:44.880 --> 00:02:47.360
I don't know-- 400 hours
of standing in front

00:02:47.360 --> 00:02:48.360
of the bathroom mirror--

00:02:48.360 --> 00:02:49.500
I was sort of a
weird little kid--

00:02:49.500 --> 00:02:50.875
standing in front
of the bathroom

00:02:50.875 --> 00:02:52.577
mirror practicing
this over and over.

00:02:52.577 --> 00:02:53.910
For some kids, it's video games.

00:02:53.910 --> 00:02:55.159
For other kids, it's football.

00:02:55.159 --> 00:02:58.020
For me, it was mastering,
as a nine year old,

00:02:58.020 --> 00:02:59.400
this coin vanish.

00:02:59.400 --> 00:03:03.992
And my mom-- because I'd
stand in front of the mirror

00:03:03.992 --> 00:03:06.450
and practice, and I'd drop the
coin over and over and over.

00:03:06.450 --> 00:03:08.670
She went out and got a carpet
sample and put it on the floor

00:03:08.670 --> 00:03:10.350
so it wouldn't
make so much noise.

00:03:10.350 --> 00:03:13.530
But after months
of this, there was

00:03:13.530 --> 00:03:15.900
a point where it didn't
look like a trick

00:03:15.900 --> 00:03:20.432
anymore, where I closed my hand
and opened it, and the coin--

00:03:20.432 --> 00:03:22.210
it just disappeared.

00:03:22.210 --> 00:03:26.880
And I decided that I wanted to
see how people would respond

00:03:26.880 --> 00:03:28.770
to that if I did it at school.

00:03:28.770 --> 00:03:33.060
The thing that I couldn't
really have known then

00:03:33.060 --> 00:03:37.830
that I've learned since, is that
when you watch a magician, when

00:03:37.830 --> 00:03:41.820
you buy a ticket to see my show
or you see a magician on TV,

00:03:41.820 --> 00:03:45.150
you understand that you
are seeing an illusion.

00:03:45.150 --> 00:03:46.470
Magic is fiction.

00:03:46.470 --> 00:03:50.370
And it's just part of the
form that the audience knows

00:03:50.370 --> 00:03:51.840
that they are being deceived.

00:03:51.840 --> 00:03:53.310
That's why everyone shows up--

00:03:53.310 --> 00:03:56.940
to see something that
they can't explain.

00:03:56.940 --> 00:03:59.400
When you don't
have that context,

00:03:59.400 --> 00:04:00.840
magic isn't entertaining.

00:04:00.840 --> 00:04:01.741
It's just terrifying.

00:04:01.741 --> 00:04:03.990
If I were to just stand here
in front of you right now

00:04:03.990 --> 00:04:07.230
and disappear, the
appropriate response to that

00:04:07.230 --> 00:04:08.490
would not be to clap.

00:04:08.490 --> 00:04:11.100
It would be like, get up and
run as quickly as you can

00:04:11.100 --> 00:04:12.390
from this room.

00:04:12.390 --> 00:04:15.660
So the kids watching
on the playground

00:04:15.660 --> 00:04:18.296
didn't know that they
were seeing a magic trick.

00:04:18.296 --> 00:04:19.920
They didn't know that
I was a magician.

00:04:19.920 --> 00:04:21.086
Because I wasn't a magician.

00:04:21.086 --> 00:04:23.100
I was just a kid who
had mastered this trick.

00:04:23.100 --> 00:04:26.370
So they saw the coin disappear,
and they didn't clap.

00:04:26.370 --> 00:04:27.120
They didn't laugh.

00:04:27.120 --> 00:04:28.590
They didn't applaud.

00:04:28.590 --> 00:04:32.610
They just started
shrieking and running away.

00:04:32.610 --> 00:04:34.440
So imagine for a
second that you're

00:04:34.440 --> 00:04:36.132
the teacher on duty
at the schoolyard,

00:04:36.132 --> 00:04:37.590
and you look across
the playground,

00:04:37.590 --> 00:04:40.210
and you see this group of
children screaming and running.

00:04:40.210 --> 00:04:42.900
And I'm standing in the middle.

00:04:42.900 --> 00:04:46.800
So this teacher stormed
across the playground.

00:04:46.800 --> 00:04:48.930
And I was terrified
of this woman.

00:04:48.930 --> 00:04:53.100
And she towered
above me and demanded

00:04:53.100 --> 00:04:55.860
that I show her whatever
it was that I showed

00:04:55.860 --> 00:04:58.240
the kids to make them run away.

00:04:58.240 --> 00:05:01.470
And so I took the coin
out, and put it in my hand,

00:05:01.470 --> 00:05:04.690
and did my little
dance of the fingers.

00:05:04.690 --> 00:05:12.150
And when I opened it, it was
like she was a little kid.

00:05:12.150 --> 00:05:14.910
I had never seen
any adult anywhere

00:05:14.910 --> 00:05:19.260
respond to anything the
way this grown, educated,

00:05:19.260 --> 00:05:23.490
terrifying woman was
reacting to this coin vanish.

00:05:23.490 --> 00:05:26.970
And I suppose
that's a fun story.

00:05:26.970 --> 00:05:29.010
But for me, it was
very troubling.

00:05:29.010 --> 00:05:31.110
Because I knew it
was just a trick.

00:05:31.110 --> 00:05:33.100
I knew that I was
just a little kid who

00:05:33.100 --> 00:05:34.680
had learned a coin trick.

00:05:34.680 --> 00:05:39.690
And I could not
explain the disparity

00:05:39.690 --> 00:05:46.980
between the very simple means
and the staggeringly unexpected

00:05:46.980 --> 00:05:50.130
result that came from something
as simple as a coin trick.

00:05:50.130 --> 00:05:53.619
So I didn't become
a magician because I

00:05:53.619 --> 00:05:54.660
wanted to be a performer.

00:05:54.660 --> 00:05:56.160
I didn't become a
magician because I

00:05:56.160 --> 00:05:59.480
wanted to be in entertainment
or get on stage.

00:05:59.480 --> 00:06:02.100
It's like I discovered,
at a really young age,

00:06:02.100 --> 00:06:04.440
that you can say something
with a magic trick that's

00:06:04.440 --> 00:06:06.240
hard to say any other way.

00:06:06.240 --> 00:06:08.880
And I just wanted to chase
that as far as I could.

00:06:13.427 --> 00:06:17.580
I think it's one thing as a
nine year old to say that you're

00:06:17.580 --> 00:06:19.350
going to become the
greatest magician

00:06:19.350 --> 00:06:21.160
in the history of the world.

00:06:21.160 --> 00:06:24.380
It's another thing to say
that as a 19 year old.

00:06:24.380 --> 00:06:27.900
And I went to college
on an acting scholarship

00:06:27.900 --> 00:06:30.870
because I wanted
to study stagecraft

00:06:30.870 --> 00:06:33.180
because I thought it would
lead me to become a better

00:06:33.180 --> 00:06:34.420
performer.

00:06:34.420 --> 00:06:38.010
But what I learned instead
was that the best way

00:06:38.010 --> 00:06:40.140
to learn magic is to
just do it for people,

00:06:40.140 --> 00:06:43.170
to do it for anyone you can find
in all different walks of life.

00:06:43.170 --> 00:06:46.080
And the discovery
that I made is that it

00:06:46.080 --> 00:06:47.370
doesn't matter who you are.

00:06:47.370 --> 00:06:49.440
You can be young,
old, rich, poor.

00:06:49.440 --> 00:06:50.820
You can be a
sheepherder in Tibet

00:06:50.820 --> 00:06:52.050
or a taxi driver in Texas.

00:06:52.050 --> 00:06:52.810
It doesn't matter.

00:06:52.810 --> 00:06:55.770
Everyone everywhere
in the world responds

00:06:55.770 --> 00:06:58.710
to a good piece of magic
in exactly the same way.

00:06:58.710 --> 00:07:01.470
It's like this
universal experience.

00:07:01.470 --> 00:07:04.920
The question that
I've been chasing

00:07:04.920 --> 00:07:07.605
as a magician for as long as
I can remember is very simple.

00:07:10.510 --> 00:07:13.540
I've noticed that
as I get older,

00:07:13.540 --> 00:07:19.380
it becomes harder for me to be
genuinely amazed by anything.

00:07:19.380 --> 00:07:22.620
To be clear, it's easy
to be entertained.

00:07:22.620 --> 00:07:24.370
It's easy to be inspired.

00:07:24.370 --> 00:07:26.490
It's also easy to be
deceived or fooled.

00:07:26.490 --> 00:07:30.240
All of the experiences that
are in orbit around wonder

00:07:30.240 --> 00:07:31.900
are relatively common.

00:07:31.900 --> 00:07:36.000
But for me, that white
light through the clouds--

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:38.370
astonishment-- does
get harder and harder

00:07:38.370 --> 00:07:39.846
to find as I get older.

00:07:39.846 --> 00:07:41.220
I think one of
the reasons I love

00:07:41.220 --> 00:07:45.570
magic so much is it's a
way for me to chase that.

00:07:45.570 --> 00:07:48.300
But even as a young magician--

00:07:48.300 --> 00:07:51.210
I feel like in every
profession, you probably

00:07:51.210 --> 00:07:53.880
get to see a corner of the
human experience that's harder

00:07:53.880 --> 00:07:55.380
to see from another profession.

00:07:55.380 --> 00:07:57.690
Doctors probably see
things in waiting rooms

00:07:57.690 --> 00:07:59.664
that you don't
see anywhere else.

00:07:59.664 --> 00:08:01.080
I don't know what
architects learn

00:08:01.080 --> 00:08:02.520
about being a human
being, but I'm

00:08:02.520 --> 00:08:03.950
sure there's something there.

00:08:03.950 --> 00:08:07.230
But for magicians, especially
as a young magician,

00:08:07.230 --> 00:08:13.530
it becomes impossible
to ignore the loss that

00:08:13.530 --> 00:08:16.140
happens in the
transition from being

00:08:16.140 --> 00:08:17.580
a child to being a grown-up.

00:08:17.580 --> 00:08:19.020
Because you see in all of--

00:08:19.020 --> 00:08:22.410
as a kid, I remember
doing magic for my parents

00:08:22.410 --> 00:08:24.060
and the friends of my parents.

00:08:24.060 --> 00:08:28.230
And it became clear that there
is this incredible weight that

00:08:28.230 --> 00:08:33.280
settles on people when you're an
adult. And with a magic trick,

00:08:33.280 --> 00:08:35.049
you can make that go
away for a second.

00:08:35.049 --> 00:08:37.890
I love that.

00:08:37.890 --> 00:08:44.120
I think the obvious
answer to why

00:08:44.120 --> 00:08:47.390
is it harder to become
amazed by anything

00:08:47.390 --> 00:08:49.610
as you get older than
it is when you're

00:08:49.610 --> 00:08:53.300
a kid is that when you're an
adult, you just know more.

00:08:53.300 --> 00:08:56.330
You have more information.

00:08:56.330 --> 00:09:01.350
But that answer falls apart
for me for a few reasons.

00:09:01.350 --> 00:09:07.220
I think the magician operates
from the fundamental conviction

00:09:07.220 --> 00:09:09.200
that learning more
about anything

00:09:09.200 --> 00:09:12.740
makes that thing more amazing
rather than less amazing.

00:09:12.740 --> 00:09:15.290
It's the absolute
renunciation of the axiom that

00:09:15.290 --> 00:09:18.710
familiarity breeds contempt.

00:09:18.710 --> 00:09:21.320
Just before I got married, I
was reading this book about--

00:09:21.320 --> 00:09:22.820
I was fascinated by lightning.

00:09:22.820 --> 00:09:24.960
I just wanted to
understand what it was.

00:09:24.960 --> 00:09:28.400
And so I was reading
this meteorological book.

00:09:28.400 --> 00:09:31.702
And then my wife and I
happened to be on our honeymoon

00:09:31.702 --> 00:09:33.410
in the middle of the
Canadian wilderness.

00:09:33.410 --> 00:09:35.240
We went on this
wilderness canoe trip.

00:09:35.240 --> 00:09:38.840
And we got pinned down
on an island seven days

00:09:38.840 --> 00:09:41.390
from the middle of nowhere
with this lightning

00:09:41.390 --> 00:09:42.980
storm that came in.

00:09:42.980 --> 00:09:47.210
And it was one of the most
terrifying moments in my life,

00:09:47.210 --> 00:09:51.260
because lightning was slamming
over and over and over

00:09:51.260 --> 00:09:52.640
onto the trees on our island.

00:09:52.640 --> 00:09:54.200
You could hear
trees falling, and I

00:09:54.200 --> 00:09:56.720
was worried that a tree was
going to fall on our tent.

00:09:56.720 --> 00:09:58.860
And it was terrifying.

00:09:58.860 --> 00:10:01.310
But it was also,
if I'm honest, one

00:10:01.310 --> 00:10:06.170
of the most riveting, wonderful,
wide awake moments of my life.

00:10:06.170 --> 00:10:11.310
And I reckon it was in one
scene, in one experience,

00:10:11.310 --> 00:10:17.630
the reality of lightning--

00:10:17.630 --> 00:10:20.826
I understood that understanding
the nature of lightning,

00:10:20.826 --> 00:10:23.450
understanding that it's a static
discharge from the clouds that

00:10:23.450 --> 00:10:26.450
explodes to the ground in
this cataclysmic blast--

00:10:26.450 --> 00:10:28.160
knowing the facts
about lightning

00:10:28.160 --> 00:10:30.470
does nothing to remove
the astonishment

00:10:30.470 --> 00:10:34.520
of being in the middle
of a thunderstorm.

00:10:34.520 --> 00:10:39.450
So I love magic for
a number of reasons.

00:10:39.450 --> 00:10:46.090
But one of them is that it's a
way to connect with the unknown

00:10:46.090 --> 00:10:49.850
and to make peace
with the fact that I

00:10:49.850 --> 00:10:51.030
don't have all the answers.

00:10:51.030 --> 00:10:52.760
I will never have
all the answers.

00:10:52.760 --> 00:10:56.215
And to share that
experience with an audience.

00:10:56.215 --> 00:10:57.590
A few years ago,
I decided that I

00:10:57.590 --> 00:11:01.010
wanted to write a book
about all of this--

00:11:01.010 --> 00:11:03.020
about wonder, about
disillusionment,

00:11:03.020 --> 00:11:09.470
about losing sight
of astonishment,

00:11:09.470 --> 00:11:11.450
and all of the things
that I love about magic

00:11:11.450 --> 00:11:12.380
and finding it again.

00:11:12.380 --> 00:11:14.750
And when I finished
writing the book,

00:11:14.750 --> 00:11:18.410
I was worried that it's easy to
get up and talk about wonder.

00:11:18.410 --> 00:11:20.660
It's easy to write
a book about wonder

00:11:20.660 --> 00:11:22.160
when you're sitting
in a Starbucks

00:11:22.160 --> 00:11:24.050
paying $5 for a cup of coffee.

00:11:24.050 --> 00:11:27.290
But I wanted to see if
it would still hold up

00:11:27.290 --> 00:11:30.200
if I went to the toughest,
most aggressive, most hostile

00:11:30.200 --> 00:11:31.760
place I could find.

00:11:31.760 --> 00:11:35.300
So I asked a warden of a
maximum security prison

00:11:35.300 --> 00:11:39.080
if I could come in to do
magic for the inmates.

00:11:39.080 --> 00:11:42.110
And it was one of the
most incredible events

00:11:42.110 --> 00:11:43.230
of my entire career.

00:11:43.230 --> 00:11:44.990
I'd like to show you
the video, but here's

00:11:44.990 --> 00:11:46.820
what I want you to see.

00:11:46.820 --> 00:11:51.324
Before the magic happens, they
wanted nothing to do with it.

00:11:51.324 --> 00:11:52.740
They wanted nothing
to do with it.

00:11:52.740 --> 00:11:56.690
They were standing like this,
sort of tough and antagonistic.

00:11:56.690 --> 00:12:01.130
And then you will see there is
a moment where something happens

00:12:01.130 --> 00:12:02.390
that they can't explain.

00:12:02.390 --> 00:12:04.550
And it's just like
a switch flips.

00:12:04.550 --> 00:12:06.260
And you will see these--

00:12:06.260 --> 00:12:08.300
some of these guys are
in prison for life,

00:12:08.300 --> 00:12:09.890
and you will see them--

00:12:09.890 --> 00:12:12.320
I don't know-- become
little kids again.

00:12:12.320 --> 00:12:17.131
So if I can get this video to
work, I'd like to show you.

00:12:17.131 --> 00:12:20.470
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:12:31.980 --> 00:12:33.550
- I'm going to use
a deck of cards.

00:12:33.550 --> 00:12:37.780
I'm going to give it to
you to hold for the moment.

00:12:37.780 --> 00:12:39.897
We're going to need--
here, will you name a card?

00:12:39.897 --> 00:12:40.730
- Eight of diamonds.

00:12:40.730 --> 00:12:42.600
- OK, eight of diamonds.

