00:16:24.520 --> 00:16:28.060
NATE STANIFORTH: So
when I finished college,

00:16:28.060 --> 00:16:30.910
I started touring as a
professional magician.

00:16:30.910 --> 00:16:37.480
And for me, that looked
like essentially living out

00:16:37.480 --> 00:16:40.720
of a suitcase and bouncing
around the country

00:16:40.720 --> 00:16:43.180
doing a show as often
as I could five nights

00:16:43.180 --> 00:16:46.450
a weeks, six nights a week.

00:16:46.450 --> 00:16:48.520
I think when you're an
established magician,

00:16:48.520 --> 00:16:51.490
you can tour in a circuit,
sort of like a band.

00:16:51.490 --> 00:16:53.590
So you can play
Denver one night,

00:16:53.590 --> 00:16:56.980
and Fort Collins the next night,
and maybe Colorado Springs,

00:16:56.980 --> 00:16:58.180
and work your way across.

00:16:58.180 --> 00:16:59.890
Maybe go to Lincoln,
and then Des Moines,

00:16:59.890 --> 00:17:02.204
and tour across the country.

00:17:02.204 --> 00:17:03.620
But when you're
just starting out,

00:17:03.620 --> 00:17:05.349
you have to go
wherever the work is.

00:17:05.349 --> 00:17:10.329
And so I do Tuesday in Florida,
Wednesday in California,

00:17:10.329 --> 00:17:12.980
Thursday in Ohio, just
criss-crossing the country.

00:17:12.980 --> 00:17:15.329
And I did that for five years.

00:17:15.329 --> 00:17:21.369
And I discovered that
maybe like most jobs,

00:17:21.369 --> 00:17:25.060
the profession of
magic, which I thought

00:17:25.060 --> 00:17:28.000
looked so amazing
from the outside,

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:31.810
concealed beneath that
veneer this grinding,

00:17:31.810 --> 00:17:34.300
day-to-day reality.

00:17:34.300 --> 00:17:35.620
My commute would be 15 hours.

00:17:35.620 --> 00:17:37.870
I'd wake up at 3:00 in the
morning to get to the show,

00:17:37.870 --> 00:17:40.537
and then do sound check and
load in, and do the show,

00:17:40.537 --> 00:17:42.370
and then go to bed and
sleep for four hours,

00:17:42.370 --> 00:17:43.750
and then get up and
do that all again

00:17:43.750 --> 00:17:46.041
the next night, and the next
night, and the next night.

00:17:46.041 --> 00:17:49.450
And after five years,
I just ran into a wall.

00:17:49.450 --> 00:17:52.370
I just felt like I
couldn't do it anymore.

00:17:52.370 --> 00:17:55.090
I was onstage in
Milwaukee in front

00:17:55.090 --> 00:17:57.924
of-- it was a beautiful
auditorium, a great audience,

00:17:57.924 --> 00:17:59.090
and the show was going well.

00:17:59.090 --> 00:18:01.360
And in the middle of the
show, I just said, I'm sorry.

00:18:01.360 --> 00:18:01.870
I'm done.

00:18:01.870 --> 00:18:04.990
I hope you had a good time,
but I'm going to go now.

00:18:04.990 --> 00:18:07.180
I walked off in the
middle of the set

00:18:07.180 --> 00:18:11.980
and went back to my
hotel room and thought,

00:18:11.980 --> 00:18:13.750
maybe this ship is sinking.

00:18:13.750 --> 00:18:18.850
Maybe I'm not going to do
this anymore, because I do not

00:18:18.850 --> 00:18:21.610
want to have this be what my--

00:18:21.610 --> 00:18:23.815
I don't want my life to
look like this anymore.

00:18:26.790 --> 00:18:31.090
The universe, I think, is a
strange and mysterious place.

00:18:31.090 --> 00:18:35.560
And once in a while,
incredible things just happen.

00:18:35.560 --> 00:18:38.830
And it just so happened that
on this leg of the tour,

00:18:38.830 --> 00:18:41.740
I happened to be
reading this book

00:18:41.740 --> 00:18:45.700
about traditional
Indian street magic.

00:18:45.700 --> 00:18:49.240
Every culture in the
world has its own version

00:18:49.240 --> 00:18:53.170
of the archetypal
figure of the magician.

00:18:53.170 --> 00:18:56.950
Just like food or art
or music, the magic

00:18:56.950 --> 00:19:00.490
that comes from a
culture is as much

00:19:00.490 --> 00:19:04.840
an expression of that culture
as any of the other arts.

00:19:04.840 --> 00:19:07.960
So had I been reading a book
about Chinese traditional

00:19:07.960 --> 00:19:09.720
magic, I would have
wanted to go to China,

00:19:09.720 --> 00:19:12.950
or Japanese magic, maybe I would
have wanted to go to Japan.

00:19:12.950 --> 00:19:16.432
But after I walked off
in the middle of the set

00:19:16.432 --> 00:19:18.640
and went back to my hotel
room, I picked up this book

00:19:18.640 --> 00:19:19.990
and started reading it.

00:19:19.990 --> 00:19:22.480
And I decided that
what I wanted to do

00:19:22.480 --> 00:19:26.430
was walk away from
everything in the US,

00:19:26.430 --> 00:19:30.460
to just leave my touring career
behind and forget everything

00:19:30.460 --> 00:19:33.640
I knew about being a
magician in America,

00:19:33.640 --> 00:19:37.427
and go to the other side of the
world to see all of this magic

00:19:37.427 --> 00:19:38.260
I was reading about.

00:19:38.260 --> 00:19:39.754
So I wanted to see
snake charming.

00:19:39.754 --> 00:19:41.170
I wanted to see
street performing.

00:19:41.170 --> 00:19:43.000
I wanted to see fire breathing.

00:19:45.520 --> 00:19:48.310
It wasn't so much that I wanted
to go to India specifically.

00:19:48.310 --> 00:19:50.180
I just wanted to
go to this place

00:19:50.180 --> 00:19:53.060
where all of these things I was
reading about were performed.

00:19:53.060 --> 00:19:58.450
So my mission was I wanted
to go be amazed by something.

00:19:58.450 --> 00:20:02.579
I wanted to remember why I
loved being a magician so much

00:20:02.579 --> 00:20:04.120
by seeing a tradition
of magic that's

00:20:04.120 --> 00:20:06.400
totally different from my own.

00:20:06.400 --> 00:20:07.630
And so I did.

00:20:07.630 --> 00:20:12.580
I went to India, and I sought
out snake charmers and street

00:20:12.580 --> 00:20:13.300
performers.

00:20:13.300 --> 00:20:16.630
I found a tribe of traditional
Indian street magicians who

00:20:16.630 --> 00:20:19.120
trace their lineage and have
passed their secrets down

00:20:19.120 --> 00:20:21.750
from father to son
for 3,000 years.

00:20:21.750 --> 00:20:26.940
I saw amazing magic, so I found
what I was looking for there.

00:20:26.940 --> 00:20:30.760
But what I discovered was
that the most amazing parts

00:20:30.760 --> 00:20:36.910
of the trip, the most
genuinely magical moments that

00:20:36.910 --> 00:20:39.790
felt like I think magic should
feel, good magic should feel,

00:20:39.790 --> 00:20:41.620
had nothing to do with
tricks and nothing

00:20:41.620 --> 00:20:43.210
to do with performances.

00:20:43.210 --> 00:20:46.930
It was in immersing
myself in a new culture,

00:20:46.930 --> 00:20:49.120
seeing things I had
never seen before.

00:20:49.120 --> 00:20:53.410
Both travel and magic are
similar in their ability

00:20:53.410 --> 00:20:55.490
to deliver this
cataclysmic death

00:20:55.490 --> 00:20:59.440
blow to any sense of certainty
you have about who you are

00:20:59.440 --> 00:21:02.650
and how you fit in with
the world around you.

00:21:02.650 --> 00:21:04.870
And so I became
really fascinated

00:21:04.870 --> 00:21:11.230
with this idea of finding
wonder not in the extraordinary,

00:21:11.230 --> 00:21:12.287
but in the ordinary.

00:21:12.287 --> 00:21:14.620
It's one thing to find it on
the other side of the world

00:21:14.620 --> 00:21:16.900
or find it in a magic show,
but how do you find it

00:21:16.900 --> 00:21:18.070
in your day-to-day life?

00:21:18.070 --> 00:21:22.927
How do you-- adults are really
good at making things ordinary.

00:21:22.927 --> 00:21:24.760
We're really good at
getting used to things,

00:21:24.760 --> 00:21:26.500
which is probably useful.

00:21:26.500 --> 00:21:29.200
If we woke up every
morning and freaked out

00:21:29.200 --> 00:21:32.200
at this bright, burning
ball of thermonuclear fury

00:21:32.200 --> 00:21:36.559
rising over the east, that would
be an untenable way to live.

00:21:36.559 --> 00:21:38.850
We should just call it the
sun and get on with our day.

00:21:38.850 --> 00:21:42.580
But the danger is
that you end up

00:21:42.580 --> 00:21:46.720
shrinking your world down to
the size of your certainties.

00:21:46.720 --> 00:21:48.550
And you live in the
story you tell yourself

00:21:48.550 --> 00:21:51.640
about the world rather
than the world itself.

00:21:51.640 --> 00:21:53.650
And my favorite
moments are those

00:21:53.650 --> 00:21:58.960
that wake me up, and shake
me loose from that world

00:21:58.960 --> 00:22:02.110
that I've made for
myself, and remind me

00:22:02.110 --> 00:22:07.180
that there's more that I'm
not paying attention to.

00:22:07.180 --> 00:22:08.860
When I came back
from India, I was

00:22:08.860 --> 00:22:13.005
worried that that was a
lot to ask of a magic show.

00:22:13.005 --> 00:22:14.380
For the first
time, I felt like I

00:22:14.380 --> 00:22:16.171
had something I wanted
to say that I didn't

00:22:16.171 --> 00:22:18.415
know how to say as a magician.

00:22:18.415 --> 00:22:20.290
So I started learning
to write, and I decided

00:22:20.290 --> 00:22:21.380
I was going to write a book.

00:22:21.380 --> 00:22:23.379
And that's the book that
all of you are holding,

00:22:23.379 --> 00:22:24.910
"Here is Real Magic."

00:22:24.910 --> 00:22:29.140
When the book came out, I wanted
to invent a piece of magic that

00:22:29.140 --> 00:22:34.330
would set the stage to tell
everyone what to expect

00:22:34.330 --> 00:22:36.250
from a book by a magician.

00:22:36.250 --> 00:22:38.191
And I'd like to show it to you.

00:22:38.191 --> 00:22:38.857
