00:25:40.740 --> 00:25:43.050
NATE STANIFORTH: Of
magicians specifically?

00:25:43.050 --> 00:25:46.735
I don't want to speak to--

00:25:46.735 --> 00:25:49.110
it's hard to comment on what
other people's motives might

00:25:49.110 --> 00:25:51.150
be, so I don't want
to assume anything

00:25:51.150 --> 00:25:53.850
about other magicians
that might not be true.

00:25:53.850 --> 00:25:58.320
But I think you probably
have the same thing

00:25:58.320 --> 00:25:59.410
in music as well.

00:25:59.410 --> 00:26:02.670
Some people get into
music because they

00:26:02.670 --> 00:26:08.010
want to be rock stars, and they
want to have everybody scream

00:26:08.010 --> 00:26:10.239
and go crazy, and they
want to be famous.

00:26:10.239 --> 00:26:12.030
And then you have people
who get into music

00:26:12.030 --> 00:26:14.610
because they love music,
and they love writing songs.

00:26:14.610 --> 00:26:17.680
And I'm not saying one
is better than another.

00:26:17.680 --> 00:26:22.260
But for me, being
a performer is--

00:26:22.260 --> 00:26:24.990
it's something-- I've made
my peace with it, for sure,

00:26:24.990 --> 00:26:26.910
but that's not why
I got into magic.

00:26:26.910 --> 00:26:30.030
I got into it because
I love the thing that I

00:26:30.030 --> 00:26:33.860
am able to chase as a magician.

00:26:33.860 --> 00:26:38.160
And if I could do it better
as a musician, maybe I would.

00:26:38.160 --> 00:26:41.070
Magic has a lot of
cultural baggage to it.

00:26:41.070 --> 00:26:48.800
But I just-- personally, I
love the experience of magic.

00:26:48.800 --> 00:26:51.030
You don't need to do
tricks to do magic.

00:26:51.030 --> 00:26:54.360
The first time I really
remember the experience

00:26:54.360 --> 00:26:56.580
of being amazed by
something was when

00:26:56.580 --> 00:26:58.650
my parents took
me to see a meteor

00:26:58.650 --> 00:27:00.330
shower when I was a little kid.

00:27:00.330 --> 00:27:04.470
And we lived in a small college
town in the middle of Iowa.

00:27:04.470 --> 00:27:06.512
But even in a
small college town,

00:27:06.512 --> 00:27:08.220
there's enough light
pollution that makes

00:27:08.220 --> 00:27:09.570
it hard to see the Milky Way.

00:27:09.570 --> 00:27:11.640
But they woke me up in
the middle of the night

00:27:11.640 --> 00:27:13.860
and drove my brother
and sister out

00:27:13.860 --> 00:27:15.900
into the cornfields
where there's no light.

00:27:15.900 --> 00:27:17.400
And it just--

00:27:17.400 --> 00:27:22.200
I remember feeling like, where
has this been all my life?

00:27:22.200 --> 00:27:24.360
It was one of the most
amazing things, still,

00:27:24.360 --> 00:27:25.680
that I've ever seen.

00:27:25.680 --> 00:27:28.410
And I love that experience.

00:27:28.410 --> 00:27:30.550
And I'll follow that anywhere.

00:27:30.550 --> 00:27:33.240
And if that means,
as part of the job,

00:27:33.240 --> 00:27:36.000
getting up and doing a
magic show, that's fine.

00:27:36.000 --> 00:27:40.860
But I guess that's
my way of answering

00:27:40.860 --> 00:27:43.889
how I feel about it, trying
not to speak for other people.

00:27:43.889 --> 00:27:44.430
Is that fair?

00:27:44.430 --> 00:27:45.140
AUDIENCE: That's fair.

00:27:45.140 --> 00:27:45.420
NATE STANIFORTH: OK.

00:27:45.420 --> 00:27:46.420
Thank you for asking.

00:27:46.420 --> 00:27:46.920
Yeah.

00:27:46.920 --> 00:27:48.010
Hi.

00:27:48.010 --> 00:27:50.580
AUDIENCE: So you mentioned
that when we see a magic show,

00:27:50.580 --> 00:27:52.460
we know it's an illusion.

00:27:52.460 --> 00:27:55.220
And part of the fun is
trying to see how it's done.

00:27:55.220 --> 00:27:57.870
[INAUDIBLE],, you know
it could be failing.

00:27:57.870 --> 00:27:59.850
When you go to see a
magic show, obviously, it

00:27:59.850 --> 00:28:01.500
must be quite a
different experience,

00:28:01.500 --> 00:28:03.900
because you have a
pretty good idea how

00:28:03.900 --> 00:28:06.855
a lot of the common
effects are done.

00:28:09.420 --> 00:28:12.180
That must change the experience
for you quite a lot to one

00:28:12.180 --> 00:28:19.260
of being amazed to one of
trying to see how it's done.

00:28:19.260 --> 00:28:23.970
How often do you find yourself
astonished and amazed by magic?

00:28:23.970 --> 00:28:28.440
NATE STANIFORTH: So I'd like
to answer that in two parts.

00:28:28.440 --> 00:28:32.790
So the experience I'm having
now, having written this book,

00:28:32.790 --> 00:28:36.690
is now that I have been
through the process

00:28:36.690 --> 00:28:38.190
of writing a book myself--

00:28:38.190 --> 00:28:41.070
and it took four years
of pretty rigorous work.

00:28:41.070 --> 00:28:42.990
When I read other
people's work, I

00:28:42.990 --> 00:28:48.480
feel like sometimes I can
see the joints and the beams

00:28:48.480 --> 00:28:50.890
and the girders in a way
that I couldn't before.

00:28:50.890 --> 00:28:54.820
And it has changed the way
I read certainly memoirs,

00:28:54.820 --> 00:28:58.500
too, because now I have this
professional relationship

00:28:58.500 --> 00:29:02.490
with that form that necessarily
changes the way I take it in.

00:29:02.490 --> 00:29:04.870
That's been true for
magic for a long time.

00:29:04.870 --> 00:29:08.440
And as you say, it's hard
not to watch a magic show

00:29:08.440 --> 00:29:10.210
and deconstruct it.

00:29:10.210 --> 00:29:14.220
But I would say that
like the best writers,

00:29:14.220 --> 00:29:17.310
you read some books,
and there are no seams.

00:29:17.310 --> 00:29:20.590
It's just like it arrived fully
formed from some other world.

00:29:20.590 --> 00:29:22.770
A great magic show
is that way too.

00:29:22.770 --> 00:29:27.780
And in the book, I
describe one piece of magic

00:29:27.780 --> 00:29:30.760
that I witnessed that--

00:29:30.760 --> 00:29:33.010
I saw it in 2013, and
I've thought about it,

00:29:33.010 --> 00:29:36.610
without exaggeration,
every day since 2013.

00:29:36.610 --> 00:29:37.940
And I still can't explain it.

00:29:37.940 --> 00:29:38.830
And I love that.

00:29:38.830 --> 00:29:42.160
I love the realization
that no matter how far

00:29:42.160 --> 00:29:44.560
I push this craft,
there are still people

00:29:44.560 --> 00:29:46.297
who are so far ahead of me.

00:29:46.297 --> 00:29:47.880
Rather than being
intimidated by that,

00:29:47.880 --> 00:29:50.380
I really love that,
because it means

00:29:50.380 --> 00:29:55.555
that I can still find that
spark of inspiration as well.

00:29:55.555 --> 00:29:57.070
Is that a fair answer?

00:29:57.070 --> 00:29:57.625
Yeah.

00:29:57.625 --> 00:29:58.900
OK.

00:29:58.900 --> 00:29:59.680
Hi.

00:29:59.680 --> 00:30:02.160
AUDIENCE: So given everything
that you've been through,

00:30:02.160 --> 00:30:06.624
and going through the process of
writing the book, what's next?

00:30:06.624 --> 00:30:08.290
NATE STANIFORTH:
That's a good question.

00:30:08.290 --> 00:30:09.360
Yeah.

00:30:09.360 --> 00:30:11.800
I discovered that I
really love book writing.

00:30:11.800 --> 00:30:13.840
I feel like I snuck into
this incredible party,

00:30:13.840 --> 00:30:16.452
and I very much don't
want to leave now.

00:30:16.452 --> 00:30:18.550
So I've got other books
that I'd like to write.

00:30:18.550 --> 00:30:22.420
And in the course of writing the
book, there was a lot of work

00:30:22.420 --> 00:30:24.070
as a magician that
I didn't do that I'm

00:30:24.070 --> 00:30:25.360
catching up on as well.

00:30:25.360 --> 00:30:27.940
So I'm trying to
have it both ways

00:30:27.940 --> 00:30:31.090
and have this career where I
can go on tour twice a year

00:30:31.090 --> 00:30:32.050
and write books.

00:30:32.050 --> 00:30:34.510
And we'll see if I
can stick the landing.

00:30:34.510 --> 00:30:36.300
But that's very much the goal.

00:30:36.300 --> 00:30:38.870
So thanks for asking.

00:30:38.870 --> 00:30:39.719
Hi.

00:30:39.719 --> 00:30:40.260
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:30:40.260 --> 00:30:42.290
What advice would you
give today to that 9,

00:30:42.290 --> 00:30:44.310
10-year-old boy or
girl getting into magic

00:30:44.310 --> 00:30:46.060
and wants to do magic?

00:30:49.540 --> 00:30:51.540
NATE STANIFORTH: There's
this quote from Houdini

00:30:51.540 --> 00:30:53.290
that I discovered when
I was a little kid.

00:30:53.290 --> 00:30:54.690
You're all familiar
with Houdini?

00:30:54.690 --> 00:30:55.590
Yeah.

00:30:55.590 --> 00:30:58.710
So Houdini said--

00:30:58.710 --> 00:31:02.280
Houdini was like the
original Gary Vaynerchuk.

00:31:02.280 --> 00:31:06.040
He said, the real secret
to my success is simple.

00:31:06.040 --> 00:31:09.270
I work from 7:00 AM to
midnight, and I like it.

00:31:09.270 --> 00:31:14.310
And I think one of the reasons
I latched on to magic is

00:31:14.310 --> 00:31:19.050
because I just really liked that
monk-like existence of having

00:31:19.050 --> 00:31:20.790
one--

00:31:20.790 --> 00:31:21.970
my life was very simple.

00:31:21.970 --> 00:31:25.890
I had one job, and it
was to perfect this craft

00:31:25.890 --> 00:31:28.380
to the exclusion of
basically anything else.

00:31:28.380 --> 00:31:31.260
And I think whether you're
interested in magic or music

00:31:31.260 --> 00:31:36.667
or poetry or
basket-weaving or whatever,

00:31:36.667 --> 00:31:39.000
I think there's a lot to be
said for just working harder

00:31:39.000 --> 00:31:41.416
than the other people who are
trying to do the same thing.

00:31:41.416 --> 00:31:44.490
Because that's the one
thing you can control.

00:31:44.490 --> 00:31:47.220
There are other people who are
more gifted performers or more

00:31:47.220 --> 00:31:49.020
charismatic communicators.

00:31:49.020 --> 00:31:55.410
But the one point where I
get to choose how I react

00:31:55.410 --> 00:31:58.550
is just working harder
than everybody else.

00:31:58.550 --> 00:32:01.380
And I don't know.

00:32:01.380 --> 00:32:04.145
I think it doesn't suit
everybody, but it suits me.

00:32:04.145 --> 00:32:04.645
Yeah.

00:32:07.087 --> 00:32:09.420
AUDIENCE: I think you were
talking about lightening when

00:32:09.420 --> 00:32:10.530
you brought this
up, but you talked

00:32:10.530 --> 00:32:12.300
about how as you
learned more about it,

00:32:12.300 --> 00:32:15.510
it increased the amount
of wonder and awe in it.

00:32:15.510 --> 00:32:17.295
Does that apply
with magic tricks?

00:32:17.295 --> 00:32:18.670
NATE STANIFORTH:
Certainly, yeah.

00:32:18.670 --> 00:32:19.740
AUDIENCE: Even when
you learn more about

00:32:19.740 --> 00:32:21.828
how the trick is done,
you're more inspired by it?

00:32:21.828 --> 00:32:22.744
NATE STANIFORTH: Yeah.

00:32:22.744 --> 00:32:23.770
AUDIENCE: Can you explain that?

00:32:23.770 --> 00:32:24.840
That seems counter-intuitive.

00:32:24.840 --> 00:32:26.006
NATE STANIFORTH: Absolutely.

00:32:26.006 --> 00:32:30.450
I think one of the things
that you discover as you--

00:32:33.360 --> 00:32:35.550
I'm going to say explore
the craft of magic--

00:32:35.550 --> 00:32:38.330
I assume this is true
with music, or with art,

00:32:38.330 --> 00:32:41.490
with painting, or poetry,
or writing, or whatever.

00:32:41.490 --> 00:32:46.860
But the better you get,
the larger your awareness

00:32:46.860 --> 00:32:48.720
of how far you have to go.

00:32:48.720 --> 00:32:53.340
The distance between good and
great becomes much clearer.

00:32:53.340 --> 00:32:57.360
When I was starting
out, it was harder

00:32:57.360 --> 00:32:59.730
to understand
exactly what it would

00:32:59.730 --> 00:33:04.660
take to take an illusion all the
way to the point of perfection.

00:33:04.660 --> 00:33:06.490
And I think the closer
you get to that,

00:33:06.490 --> 00:33:10.470
the easier it is to see
how almost impossible

00:33:10.470 --> 00:33:15.638
it is to become as good as
some of the greats have been.

00:33:18.510 --> 00:33:20.930
Magic is interesting.

00:33:20.930 --> 00:33:23.250
I think of magic like fiction.

00:33:23.250 --> 00:33:24.705
It's easy to think that--

00:33:27.175 --> 00:33:28.800
with a magic trick,
it's easy to assume

00:33:28.800 --> 00:33:34.710
that once you know the answer,
you can stop thinking about it.

00:33:34.710 --> 00:33:36.810
But I think a good
piece of magic,

00:33:36.810 --> 00:33:39.930
like a good
fictional character--

00:33:39.930 --> 00:33:42.870
you don't finish
"Catcher in the Rye"

00:33:42.870 --> 00:33:45.630
and then say, well,
that was a good story,

00:33:45.630 --> 00:33:49.980
but Holden Caulfield wasn't a
real kid, so who cares anymore?

00:33:49.980 --> 00:33:53.790
A good novelist is using
the craft of deception.

00:33:53.790 --> 00:33:55.020
Let's be clear about that.

00:33:55.020 --> 00:33:57.450
He's making, or she's making
things up that aren't true

00:33:57.450 --> 00:33:59.820
and pulling you into
this imaginary world

00:33:59.820 --> 00:34:01.470
to give you something real.

00:34:01.470 --> 00:34:04.770
And in my experience,
the better I

00:34:04.770 --> 00:34:07.320
get as a magician,
the more I become

00:34:07.320 --> 00:34:09.510
aware of the complexities
that are involved

00:34:09.510 --> 00:34:11.940
in actually doing that well.

00:34:11.940 --> 00:34:13.230
Does that begin to--

00:34:13.230 --> 00:34:14.190
is that a fair answer?

00:34:14.190 --> 00:34:15.121
Does that-- yeah.

00:34:15.121 --> 00:34:15.620
OK.

00:34:17.989 --> 00:34:18.489
Hi.

00:34:18.489 --> 00:34:22.969
AUDIENCE: I've got a son
who's stumbled into magic

00:34:22.969 --> 00:34:24.270
and is really into it.

00:34:24.270 --> 00:34:26.094
NATE STANIFORTH: I'd
watch out for that.

00:34:26.094 --> 00:34:28.510
AUDIENCE: Sometimes it's to
the exclusion of other things,

00:34:28.510 --> 00:34:31.451
like homework.

00:34:31.451 --> 00:34:34.049
But he's gotten to the
point where he's starting

00:34:34.049 --> 00:34:35.139
to get really good at it.

00:34:35.139 --> 00:34:39.175
He can go to parties with
adults and do a card trick,

00:34:39.175 --> 00:34:41.121
and the adults are stumped.

00:34:41.121 --> 00:34:42.996
And the same reaction
that you're looking for

00:34:42.996 --> 00:34:44.739
is the reaction
that he's getting.

00:34:44.739 --> 00:34:48.170
And he's falling
in love with it.

00:34:48.170 --> 00:34:54.244
So my question for you is
how many times did people

00:34:54.244 --> 00:34:55.010
tell you--

00:34:55.010 --> 00:34:56.760
your mom grabbed the
carpet out and put it

00:34:56.760 --> 00:34:57.760
on the floor for you.

00:34:57.760 --> 00:35:00.100
How many times did
people discourage you,

00:35:00.100 --> 00:35:03.050
and how did you
get over the hump?

00:35:03.050 --> 00:35:04.340
NATE STANIFORTH: All the time.

00:35:04.340 --> 00:35:12.750
I mean, basically everyone, I
think for the best of reasons.

00:35:12.750 --> 00:35:16.640
It seems to be the
prudent thing to do

00:35:16.640 --> 00:35:18.530
to discourage
someone from becoming

00:35:18.530 --> 00:35:19.760
a professional magician.

00:35:19.760 --> 00:35:21.330
Of course.

00:35:21.330 --> 00:35:26.232
It's not-- joining the circus,
it's becoming the circus.

00:35:26.232 --> 00:35:30.980
But I think sometimes, you
know something about yourself

00:35:30.980 --> 00:35:32.840
that you can't
prove to the people

00:35:32.840 --> 00:35:35.330
in your life in any other
way but by doing it.

00:35:38.450 --> 00:35:41.030
There were a number of years,
especially when I was first

00:35:41.030 --> 00:35:44.060
working as a professional
magician, where I think

00:35:44.060 --> 00:35:45.770
basically, everyone
who cared about me

00:35:45.770 --> 00:35:50.200
was terrified that I would
be unemployed in two years.

00:35:50.200 --> 00:35:52.890
And they were probably
right to be concerned.

00:35:52.890 --> 00:35:58.320
But I knew that I was doing
what I was supposed to be doing.

00:35:58.320 --> 00:36:01.835
And it's like I didn't even
care what they thought.

00:36:01.835 --> 00:36:03.960
I just knew that I could
do it, and then show them,

00:36:03.960 --> 00:36:05.210
and then that would be enough.

00:36:10.160 --> 00:36:15.860
I think that anyone who makes
it in a profession like magic

00:36:15.860 --> 00:36:18.400
only--

00:36:18.400 --> 00:36:20.150
I think the only people
that make it don't

00:36:20.150 --> 00:36:21.380
care what anyone else says.

00:36:25.160 --> 00:36:29.060
After shows, sometimes
young magicians

00:36:29.060 --> 00:36:32.360
come up to me asking if they
should make the jump to being

00:36:32.360 --> 00:36:33.530
a professional.

00:36:33.530 --> 00:36:35.030
And I never know
how to answer that,

00:36:35.030 --> 00:36:36.410
because the only ones
who will ever make it

00:36:36.410 --> 00:36:38.300
are the ones who are so
committed to doing it

00:36:38.300 --> 00:36:40.220
that they don't care
what I have to say.

00:36:40.220 --> 00:36:44.570
And I don't know what
advice to give you,

00:36:44.570 --> 00:36:49.350
because it almost seems like--

00:36:49.350 --> 00:36:51.140
it's such a hard way
to make a living,

00:36:51.140 --> 00:36:52.970
and it's such a hard
field to gain traction

00:36:52.970 --> 00:37:02.130
in that unless that motivation,
that fire comes from within,

00:37:02.130 --> 00:37:03.180
it's not going to happen.

00:37:03.180 --> 00:37:05.960
So maybe discouraging him
is the right thing to do.

00:37:05.960 --> 00:37:06.630
I don't know.

00:37:06.630 --> 00:37:08.330
I think you can
split the difference.

00:37:08.330 --> 00:37:12.750
I think you can be realistic
and supportive at the same time.

00:37:12.750 --> 00:37:15.058
And if you figure that
out, you let me know.

00:37:15.058 --> 00:37:16.891
I have a five year old
and a three year old.

00:37:19.660 --> 00:37:21.166
But good luck either way.

00:37:21.166 --> 00:37:21.940
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

00:37:21.940 --> 00:37:22.920
NATE STANIFORTH: Yeah.

00:37:22.920 --> 00:37:23.530
Hi.

00:37:23.530 --> 00:37:25.080
AUDIENCE: So you've been doing
it for a really long time.

00:37:25.080 --> 00:37:27.459
Do you have any stories
of the craziest reactions

00:37:27.459 --> 00:37:28.250
that you've gotten?

00:37:28.250 --> 00:37:30.530
Or has anyone gotten aggressive
after you fooled them

00:37:30.530 --> 00:37:33.170
with a trick, or
anything [INAUDIBLE]??

00:37:33.170 --> 00:37:37.490
NATE STANIFORTH: I was
onstage in Danville, Virginia.

00:37:37.490 --> 00:37:42.470
And I had just done a piece
of magic with someone onstage,

00:37:42.470 --> 00:37:46.010
and he felt as if I
had read his mind.

00:37:48.690 --> 00:37:51.710
And he was conflicted
about that.

00:37:51.710 --> 00:37:52.970
There was tension in the room.

00:37:52.970 --> 00:37:54.470
It wasn't like, oh,
this is amazing.

00:37:54.470 --> 00:37:55.180
We're having fun.

00:37:55.180 --> 00:37:58.790
It was like, burn this guy.

00:37:58.790 --> 00:38:02.330
And he went back to
his seat and just sat

00:38:02.330 --> 00:38:06.440
there festering for 90 seconds.

00:38:06.440 --> 00:38:09.172
And then he stood up on his
chair-- and this was a theater,

00:38:09.172 --> 00:38:10.130
so there were armrests.

00:38:10.130 --> 00:38:13.550
And he climbed up on the
armrests to get my attention,

00:38:13.550 --> 00:38:14.450
which worked.

00:38:14.450 --> 00:38:17.162
And pointed at me and
said, to hell with you.

00:38:17.162 --> 00:38:17.870
You're the devil.

00:38:17.870 --> 00:38:19.310
I'm out of here.

00:38:19.310 --> 00:38:21.220
And stormed out of the room.

00:38:21.220 --> 00:38:23.050
The highlight of my career.

00:38:25.960 --> 00:38:28.450
So I'm just putting
that out there.

00:38:28.450 --> 00:38:32.510
But yeah, I think like we were
talking about at the beginning,

00:38:32.510 --> 00:38:33.999
when magic feels like a trick--

00:38:33.999 --> 00:38:34.790
and let's be clear.

00:38:34.790 --> 00:38:37.130
Most magic does
feel like a trick.

00:38:37.130 --> 00:38:40.100
You can take the same piece of
magic and perform it 100 times,

00:38:40.100 --> 00:38:42.560
and 99 of those times,
it will only ever

00:38:42.560 --> 00:38:46.040
feel like a competently done
piece of sleight of hand.

00:38:46.040 --> 00:38:50.150
But through some
mysterious combination

00:38:50.150 --> 00:38:54.530
of atmosphere and expectation
and technical ability and just

00:38:54.530 --> 00:38:58.070
coincidence, sometimes
the air is just right,

00:38:58.070 --> 00:39:02.280
and it resonates on a
totally different level.

00:39:02.280 --> 00:39:03.770
And then people go crazy.

00:39:03.770 --> 00:39:07.970
And yeah, I feel
like magicians get

00:39:07.970 --> 00:39:10.430
to see a very beautiful
side of people.

00:39:10.430 --> 00:39:13.550
Because I think we all are
performing for each other

00:39:13.550 --> 00:39:14.350
all the time.

00:39:14.350 --> 00:39:17.030
We all choose the clothes
we wear and the language,

00:39:17.030 --> 00:39:18.580
the vocabulary that we use.

00:39:18.580 --> 00:39:22.960
We're all putting off an
image of ourselves the way

00:39:22.960 --> 00:39:25.300
we want to be
received or perceived.

00:39:25.300 --> 00:39:28.052
And a great thing about
magic, when it's really good,

